{"title_page": "Cinderella (Disney character)", "text_new": "{{Infobox character \n| colour             = #BCD4E6\n| name               = Cinderella\n| series             = [[Cinderella (franchise)|Cinderella]]\n| image              = [[File:Cinderella disney.png|200px]]\n| caption            = Cinderella as she appears in Disney's ''[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]''.\n| first              = ''[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]'' (1950)\n| last               = \n| creator            = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Charles Perrault]]\n*[[Marc Davis (animator)|Marc Davis]]\n*[[Eric Larson]]\n*[[Les Clark]]\n*[[Mark Henn]]\n*[[Walt Disney]]}}\n| lbl1               = Based on\n| data1              = Cinderella from the [[Charles Perrault]]'s [[Cinderella|fairy tale]]\n| portrayer          = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Lily James]]<br> ([[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|2015 film]])<br>Eloise Webb {{small|(child)}}<br>([[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|2015 film]])}}\n| voice              = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Ilene Woods]]<br>([[Cinderella (1950 film)|1950 film]])\n*[[Kath Soucie]]<br>(''[[Walt Disney Parks and Resorts|Disney Parks]]'')\n*Tami Tappan<br>(singing in ''[[Cinderella III: A Twist in Time|Cinderella III]]'')\n*[[Karen Strassman]]<br>(''[[Mickey Mouse (TV series)|Mickey Mouse]]'')\n*Susan Stevens Logan<br>(studio singing voice)\n*[[Jennifer Hale]]<br><small>(2001\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| species            = <!-- if not obvious -->\n| gender             = <!-- if not obvious -->\n| occupation         = [[Scullery maid]]\n| title              = Princess\n| affiliation        = [[Disney Princess]]\n| family             = {{Plainlist|\n*Father (dies in prologue)\n*[[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Lady Tremaine|Lady Tremaine]] (stepmother)\n*[[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Drisella Tremaine|Drisella]] and [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Anastasia Tremaine|Anastasia]] Tremaine (stepsisters)\n*The Baker (step-brother-in-law)\n*The King (father-in-law)}}\n| spouse             = [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Prince Charming|Prince Charming]]\n| children           = Chad Charming (Descendants)\n| nationality        = \n}}\n'''Cinderella''' is a fictional character who appears in [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Productions]]' 12th animated feature film ''[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]'' (1950) and its [[sequel]]s ''[[Cinderella II: Dreams Come True]]'' (2002) and ''[[Cinderella III: A Twist in Time]]'' (2007). In the original film, Cinderella is voiced by American singer and actress [[Ilene Woods]]. For the sequels and subsequent film and television appearances, Woods was replaced by American actresses [[Jennifer Hale]] and Tami Tappan, who provide the character's speaking and singing voices respectively. \n\nIn the wake of her father's untimely demise, Cinderella is left in the unfortunate care of her cruel stepmother and jealous stepsisters, who constantly mistreat her, forcing Cinderella to work as a [[scullery maid]] in her own home. When Prince Charming holds a ball, the evil stepmother does not allow her to go. Cinderella, aided by her kind Fairy Godmother and equipped with a beautiful silver gown and a unique pair of glass slippers, attends, only to have to leave at [[midnight]] when the Fairy Godmother's spell is broken.\n\nReception towards Cinderella has been mixed, with some film critics describing the character as much too passive, [[Flat character|one-dimensional]], and less interesting than the film's supporting characters. Other critics found her endearing, charming, and timeless. Woods' vocal performance has also been praised. Panned or praised, Cinderella has nonetheless become one of the most famous and recognizable princesses in the history of film. With her iconic glass slippers, silver gown, hairstyle, and transformation, one of the first on-screen makeovers of its kind, the character has been established as a fashion icon, receiving accolades and recognition from ''InStyle'', ''Entertainment Weekly'', ''Glamour'' and ''Oprah.com'', as well as footwear designer and fashion icon [[Christian Louboutin]], who, in 2012, designed and released a shoe based on Cinderella's glass slippers. [[Lily James]] played a live-action version of the character in the [[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|2015 live action adaptation]] of the original 1950 film.\n\n==Development==\nThe Disney version of Cinderella was based on the French version of the tale by [[Charles Perrault]], ''Cendrillon'' written in 1697 in ''Histoires ou Contes du Temps Pass\u00e9''.<ref name=\"masterworks\">{{cite web|work=Disney Archives|title=Walt's Masterworks: Cinderella|url=http://disney.go.com/disneyatoz/familymuseum/collection/masterworks/cinderella/index.html}}</ref>\n\n===Personality===\nThe script for the original film went through revisions by various writers, sometimes with different interpretations of the character. [[Maurice Rapf]] tried to make her a less passive character than [[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]], and more rebellious against her stepfamily. Rapf explained, \"My thinking was you can't have somebody who comes in and changes everything for you. You can't be delivered it on a platter. You've got to earn it. So in my version, the Fairy Godmother said, 'It's okay till midnight but from then on it's up to you.' I made her earn it, and what she had to do to achieve it was to rebel against her stepmother and stepsisters, to stop being a slave in her own home. So I had a scene where they're ordering her around and she throws the stuff back at them. She revolts, so they lock her up in the attic. I don't think anyone took (my idea) very seriously.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mouse Under Glass: Secrets of Disney Animation & Theme Parks|last=Koenig|first=David|publisher=Bonaventure Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0964060517|location=|pages=75}}</ref>\n\n===Appearance===\nThe character was animated by [[Marc Davis (animator)|Marc Davis]] and [[Eric Larson]],<ref>{{cite book|author=Pierre Lambert|title=Walt Disney, l'\u00e2ge d'or|page=166|isbn=2950781888}}</ref> but the two animators did not have the same perception of the character, accentuating the elegance of [[Marc Davis (animator)|Davis]] and [[Eric Larson|Larson]]'s opting for simplicity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Pierre Lambert|title=Walt Disney, l'\u00e2ge d'or|page=167|isbn=2950781888}}</ref> As done with other Disney films, [[Walt Disney]] hired actress [[Helene Stanley]] to perform the live-action reference for Cinderella, that she before artists began sketching, playing the role of Cinderella in a particular scene,<ref>{{cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of Walt Disney's Animated Characters|author=John Grant|isbn=0060157771|page=228}}</ref> and artists to draw animated frames based on the movements of the actress.<ref name=\"archives\" /> She later did the same kind of work for the characters of [[Aurora (Disney)|Princess Aurora]] in ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]'' and Anita Radcliff in ''[[One Hundred and One Dalmatians|101 Dalmatians]]''.<ref name=\"archives\">{{cite web|work=Disney Archives|title=Cinderella Character History|url=http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/characters/cinderella/cinderella.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331190207/http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/characters/cinderella/cinderella.html|archivedate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Christopher Finch, author of ''The Art of Walt Disney'':{{cquote|Disney insisted that all scenes involving human characters should be shot first in live-action to determine that they would work before the expensive business of animation was permitted to start. The animators did not like this way of working, feeling it detracted from their ability to create character. However, they understood the necessity for this approach in retrospect and acknowledged that Disney had handled things with considerable subtlety.<ref name=masterworks />}}\n\n===Voice===\nIn the original 1950 film, Cinderella is voiced by American singer and actress [[Ilene Woods]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.chron.com/life/style/gallery/Disney-princesses-and-the-real-voices-behind-them-72151/photo-5324428.php|title = Disney princesses and the real voices behind them|publisher = [[Hearst Newspapers, LLC]]|website = The Houston Chronicle|accessdate = March 30, 2014}}</ref> In 1948, Woods was a young eighteen-year-old singer working as a radio personality at the time and hosting her own [[eponymous]] [[radio program]] ''The Ilene Woods Show''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2010/jul/19/ilene-woods-obituary|title = Ilene Woods obituary|publisher = Guardian News and Media Limited|website = The Guardian|accessdate = March 30, 2014|date = July 19, 2010|last = Sibley|first = Brian}}</ref> While working at [[ABC Radio Network|ABC Radio]],<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://news.moviefone.ca/2010/07/02/ilene-woods-cinderella-dead-at-81/|title = Ilene Woods, Voice of Disney's 'Cinderella,' Dead at 81|website = Moviefone|publisher = Aol Inc|last = Harris|first = Scott|date = July 2, 2010|accessdate = March 30, 2014}}</ref> Woods would regularly be visited and approached by various songwriters who wanted the singer to perform their compositions, which is ultimately how she met and befriended ''Cinderella ''songwriters [[Mack David]] and [[Jerry Livingston]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=67494|title = Ilene Woods, the Voice of Cinderella, Has Passed Away|website = ComingSoon.net|date = July 2, 2010|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = CraveOnline Media, LLC}}</ref> Ultimately, David and Livingston \"would play ... an important role in Woods's career.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAt the behest of David and Livingston, casually described as \"a favor\",<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/ilene-woods-voice-of-cinderella-dies-1.911803|title = Ilene Woods, voice of Cinderella, dies|website = CBC|publisher = CBC 2014|date = July 4, 2010|accessdate = March 30, 2014}}</ref> Woods agreed to record a series of demos of three songs that the songwriters had recently written for the studio's then-upcoming animated film ''Cinderella''. Woods'' ''recorded the songs \"[[Bibbidi-Bobbidi-Boo]]\", \"So This Is Love\", and \"[[A Dream Is a Wish Your Heart Makes]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.fosters.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100704/GJNEWS02/707049934/0/citrss2|title = Ilene Woods, N.H.-born voice of Cinderella, dies at 81|date = July 4, 2010|website = Fosters.com|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = Geo. J. Foster Company|last = Reino|first = Roni}}</ref> which the songwriters then submitted to Disney himself. Upon reviewing and listening to the tracks, Disney, impressed, decided to contact Woods personally. Two days afterward, Woods received a telephone call from Disney, with whom she immediately scheduled an interview. Woods recalled in an interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', \"We met and talked for awhile, and he said, 'How would you like to be Cinderella?'\", to which she agreed.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/03/local/la-me-ilene-woods-20100703|title = Ilene Woods dies at 81; voice of Disney's Cinderella|date = July 3, 2010|accessdate = March 30, 2014|website = Los Angeles Times|publisher = Los Angeles Times|last = McLellan|first = Dennis}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nCinderella is 19 years old with medium-length strawberry-blonde hair, blue eyes, and fair complexion. After her father dies, she is forced into servitude in her own home and is  tormented by her evil stepmother, [[Lady Tremaine]], and two stepsisters, Anastasia and Drizella. Despite this, she maintains hope through her dreams and remains a kind, gentle and sweet person. She has faith that someday her dreams of happiness will come true and her kindness will be repaid. Cinderella is shown to have a down-to-earth attitude, but she is also a daydreamer.  For example, in \"Sing Sweet Nightingale\", she becomes distracted with the bubbles, allowing Lucifer to smudge the floor she was cleaning.  Also, after hearing that the Grand Duke is traveling the kingdom with the missing slipper, she dreamily dances back to the attic humming the song she heard at the ball. She is also shown to have a sarcastic side and a sharp wit.\n\nWith the help of her animal friends, she fixes up an old party dress of her mother's so she can attend a royal ball.  However, when her evil stepsisters brutally tear the dress apart, she is heartbroken and fears that her dreams will never come true until her [[Fairy Godmother]] appears, restoring Cinderella's hope by transforming her torn homemade dress into her now-iconic silver [[ball gown|gown]] with a glittering crystalline puffed peplum, a delicate laced white [[petticoat]], and puffy sleeves. Her hair is worn up in a [[French twist (hairstyle)|French twist]] supported by a silver headband with diamond earrings, silver-white opera gloves, a black diamond choker, and glass slippers.\n\nHer look was probably inspired by 1950s French haute couture, while her torn dress is clearly inspired by Salvador Dal\u00ec and Elsa Schiaparelli's Tear dress.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lugli|first1=Emanuele|title=Tear That Dress: Cinderella (1950) and Disney's Critique of Postwar Fashion|url=http://brightlightsfilm.com/tear-that-dress-off-cinderella-1950-and-disneys-critique-of-postwar-fashion/#.VeWdKtO6feR|website=Bright Lights Film Journal|accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref>\n\nAs a servant, she wears her hair down in a ponytail, held in place with a blue ribbon, sometimes supported by a white scarf and wears a brown dress with a powder blue blouse, a white apron, and black flats.\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===''Cinderella''===\n{{main|Cinderella (1950 film)}}\n[[File:Disneyland Cinderella handstogether.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Cinderella as she appears at [[Disney Parks]].]]\nAt the start of the film, the titular character Cinderella is working as a scullery maid in her own home for her cruel stepmother named Lady Tremaine and her two stepsisters named Anastasia and Drizella. Her only friends are the birds, the mice who also live in the [[manor]], including [[Gus and Jaq]], her pet dog Bruno and her father's horse Major.\n\nShe prepares breakfast for the animals and for her stepfamily before beginning her regular chores. An invitation to the ball arrives at the door and Cinderella wants to attend. Her stepmother tells her she may go under the condition that she must finish her chores and find something suitable to wear. Cinderella discovers her deceased mother's old party dress and hopes to fix it to make it more modern, but she is too busy to do so. Meanwhile, when the mice see shadows of Cinderella's stepsisters throwing down their old sash and beads, Jaq and Gus are forced to quietly retrieve them. The mice use the unwanted items to fix up the dress. Later, Cinderella fears she will not be done working in time and will not be able to attend the ball, but her friends reveal the altered dress. Cinderella is overjoyed and thanks her friends. She races down the steps just in time, but her stepsisters recognize their discarded items and accuse her of stealing their sash and beads. They tear the dress to shreds, leaving Cinderella all by herself, and she runs out to the garden, crying.\n\nHer [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Fairy Godmother|Fairy Godmother]] appears to make her dreams come true and transforms her torn dress into a beautiful shimmering silver gown. Before Cinderella leaves, her godmother warns her that the spell will be broken at midnight. At the ball, Cinderella dances with Prince Charming and they immediately fall in love with each other. As twelve o'clock approaches, she hurries to leave, hoping to prevent the spell from breaking at the ball, which could cause her to get caught by her stepmother or stepsisters. In her haste, she loses one of her glass slippers on the staircase but fails to retrieve it in time. Cinderella hurries into her coach as it prepares to leave. The spell breaks and Cinderella is in rags once more before reminiscing her dance with the prince and thanking her godmother for all she's done for her. The next day, the prince announces he will marry the maiden whose foot fits into the glass slipper. Lady Tremaine hears Cinderella humming the same song that had played at the ball and figures out Cinderella was the girl Prince Charming fell in love with. Cinderella is locked in the tower by her stepmother, who refuses to let her have the opportunity to try on the slipper, but her animal friends help her escape. She hurries downstairs to try on the glass slipper. Knowing the slipper will fit her, Lady Tremaine intentionally causes the footman to trip and shatter the slipper. Cinderella reveals that she has kept the other slipper. She tries it on, and it fits perfectly. She and the Prince are married soon after.<ref name=\"Film\">{{cite video|people=Wilfred Jackson (director)|title=[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]|publisher=[[Walt Disney]]|date=1950}}</ref>\n\n===''Cinderella II: Dreams Come True''===\n{{main|Cinderella II: Dreams Come True}}\nGus and Jaq, with help of the other mice, and the Fairy Godmother, set off to make a new book to narrate what happens after the ending of the previous story by stringing three segments of stories together, resulting in three individual stories: \"Aim to Please\", \"Tall Tail\", and \"An Uncommon Romance\". In the first story, Cinderella and Prince Charming return home and a party begins shortly afterward. In the second story, \"Tall Tail\", Cinderella works on planning to build up a festival. The mouse named Jaq in the previous film has become a human named Sir Hugh. And in the third story, \"An Uncommon Romance\", Cinderella helps her younger stepsister [[Anastasia Tremaine|Anastasia]] reconcile with the baker, even though her stepmother Lady Tremaine has forbidden it. Near the end of the film, she reads the book that the mice made for her.<ref>{{cite video|people=John Kafka (director)|title=[[Cinderella II: Dreams Come True]]|publisher=[[DisneyToon Studios]]|date=2002}}</ref>\n\n===''Cinderella III: A Twist in Time''===\n{{main|Cinderella III: A Twist in Time}}\nIn Cinderella III: A Twist in Time, Cinderella's hard-working ethics, optimism, and devotion are put to the test, when she is magically stripped away from her \"happily ever after\" by a vengeful and then magically-empowered Tremaine and is forced to jump into physical action to restore her happy life and relationship with Prince Charming. During these events, Cinderella is shown to be cunning, tactical, persistent, and a fierce rival to those who oppress her. With no magic, being forced to rely solely on her intelligence and fearlessness, Cinderella is able to defeat her stepmother, repair her relationship with a reformed Anastasia and retain her much-deserved life of happiness, proving both her independence and strong will.<ref>{{cite video|people=Frank Nissen (director)|title=[[Cinderella III: A Twist in Time]]|publisher=[[DisneyToon Studios]]|date=2007}}</ref>\n\n===''Sofia the First''===\n{{main|Sofia the First}}\nCinderella appears in the pilot movie ''[[Sofia the First|Sofia the First: Once Upon a Princess]]'', where she helps Sofia make friends with Amber, her stepsister.\n\n===\"Le Croissant de Triomphe\"===\nIn the newest editions of ''[[Mickey Mouse (TV series)|Mickey Mouse]]'' short movies, a 2013 production reflects the iconic princess in a crucial moment.\n\nCinderella appears in the third episode of ''Mickey Mouse,'' entitled ''[http://video.disney.com/watch/disneychannel-croissant-de-triomphe-4d7b3aae690a98650d776d97 Le Croissant de Triomphe]''. While a cafe owned and operated by [[Minnie Mouse|Minnie]] runs out of [[croissant]]s, she makes a phone call to receive from [[Mickey Mouse|Mickey]] an order of croissants. In order to arrive on time, Mickey hurries and flies through Paris, and accidentally lands in [[Cinderella Castle|a castle]] where [[Prince Charming]] tries to fit the crystal slipper into Cinderella's foot. She was still dressed in her regular maid clothes. At that time, Mickey accidentally passes in his motorcycle and breaks the glass slipper.\n\n===2015 film===\n[[Lily James]] portrays the character, named Ella, in Disney's 2015 live-action version of ''[[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|Cinderella]]''. Like in the original film, her father remarries after the death of her mother but after he dies as well, she then becomes the horribly mistreated servant of her stepmother Lady Tremaine and her two stepsisters, Anastasia and Drisella. They give her the nickname \"Cinderella\" when, one morning, she wakes up with [[Cinder|soot]] on her face after sleeping near the fireplace the previous night. Unlike the original film, however, she meets the Prince (named Kit) before the ball while out in the forest. She is also shown to be more assertive when she actually stands up to her stepmother in the film's final act; Lady Tremaine attempts to blackmail Ella by only agreeing to let her try on the glass slipper if Ella will make her head of the royal household and provide suitable husbands for her stepsisters, but Ella rejects this idea, refusing to give Lady Tremaine power over Kit after the way she ruined Ella's life.\n\n==In other media==\n[[File:Tokyo Disneylands cinderella castle.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Cinderella Castle]] at [[Tokyo Disneyland]].]]\n[[File:Cinderella castle day.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Cinderella Castle]] at [[Walt Disney World]].]]\nCinderella appears as one of the Disney [[Princesses of Heart]] in the ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]'' series, captured by Maleficent, who destroyed her world. The main character, [[Characters of Kingdom Hearts#Sora|Sora]], rescues Cinderella, as well as the other Princesses, and she returns home. She is only mentioned in the sequel, ''[[Kingdom Hearts II]]''. Her story prior to being captured takes place prominently with her home world, Castle of Dreams, in the prequel, ''[[Kingdom Hearts Birth by Sleep]]''; she meets Ventus, who she mistakes for a mouse despite the obvious fact he's not, Aqua and Terra. In the ''Final Mix'' version of the game, her world is seen in the Realm of Darkness at the climax, Maleficent having destroyed it and captured her.\n\nCinderella is one of the official members of the [[Disney Princess]] franchise, appearing in several related video games, albums and other merchandise. Cinderella appears as one of the [[Disney Princess]]es in the manga, [[Kilala Princess]].\n\nCinderella appears in the [[Nintendo 3DS]] game ''[[Disney Magical World]]''. Cinderella's world is one of the four Disney movie worlds accessible to the player in this game, and many characters and items related to the movie appear. Additionally, the player has the option of attending balls at Cinderella's castle.\n\nThe [[Cinderella Castle]] is an attraction at [[Walt Disney World]]'s [[Magic Kingdom]] and [[Tokyo Disneyland]] at the [[Tokyo Disney Resort]]. Both serve as globally recognized icons for their respective theme parks. Cinderella and the other Disney Princesses have a meet and greet attraction called ''Princess Fairytale Hall'' at Magic Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidethemagic.net/2012/04/walt-disney-world-reveals-new-fantasyland-dates-closer-look-at-princess-fairy-tale-hall-be-our-guest-restaurant-and-more/|title=Walt Disney World reveals New Fantasyland dates, closer look at Princess Fairy Tale Hall, Be Our Guest restaurant, and more|work=Inside the Magic|first=Ricky|last=Brigante|date=April 28, 2012|accessdate=April 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.insidethemagic.net/2013/09/princess-fairytale-hall-to-make-royal-debut-on-sept-18-as-walt-disney-world-completes-new-home-for-cinderella-rapunzel/ Princess Fairytale Hall to make royal debut on Sept 18 as Walt Disney World completes new home for Cinderella, Rapunzel] Inside the Magic, Retrieved September 7, 2013</ref>\n\nIn the season six episodes of the sitcom series ''[[Full House]]'' known as ''The House Meets The Mouse Parts 1 & 2'', Cinderella makes cameo appearances in both Parts 1 & 2. She also appears in ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing With the Stars]]'' played by [[Sabrina Bryan]] in season 15, [[Amy Purdy]] in season 18, and [[Witney Carson]] in season 22. [[Jessy Schram]] played a live-action version of the character in ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]'' and its spin-off ''[[Once Upon a Time in Wonderland]]''. [[Dania Ramirez]] portrays another version of the role in season 7 as a main character with a different storyline.\n\nCinderella, alongside other Disney Princesses, appeared in the film ''[[Ralph Breaks the Internet]]'', as was announced at the 2017 D23 Expo.<ref name=\"Princesses2\">{{cite magazine|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/07/14/wreck-it-ralph-sequel-star-wars-disney-princesses/|title=Wreck-It Ralph sequel will unite the Disney princesses \u2014 and Star Wars!|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n\n===Critical response===\nAlthough the film has garnered critical acclaim,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1004186-cinderella/|title = Cinderella (1950)|website = Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate = March 29, 2014|publisher = Flixster, Inc}}</ref> Cinderella herself has attracted mostly mixed reviews in modern times.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.decentfilms.com/reviews/cinderella1950|title = Cinderella (1950)|website = Decent Films Guide|publisher = Steven D. Greydanus|accessdate = March 28, 2014|last = Greyandus|first = Steven D.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2009/12/11/best_aamp_worst_disney_princesses|title = Best & Worst Disney Princesses|website = Starpulse.com|accessdate = March 29, 2014|date = December 11, 2009|publisher = Starpulse.com|last = Zanello|first = Michael}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' disliked the character, describing her as \"colorless.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = https://variety.com/1949/film/reviews/cinderella-3-1200416691/|title = Review: \u2018Cinderella\u2019|publisher = Variety Media, LLC|date = December 31, 1949|website = Variety|accessdate = March 28, 2014}}</ref> Calling her an \"oppressed drudge,\" ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] ''panned Cinderella, describing both her and Prince Charming as \"bland and colourless characters - particularly when compared to [[Belle (Disney)|Beauty]] and her [[Beast (Disney)|Beast]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?DVDID=116838|title = Cinderella|website = Empire|publisher = Bauer Consumer Media Ltd|accessdate = March 28, 2014|year = 2009}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]''<nowiki/>' [[Bosley Crowther]] similarly wrote, \"The beautiful Cinderella has a [[voluptuous]] face and form\u2014not to mention an eager disposition\u2014to compare with [[Al Capp]]'s [[Daisy Mae]].\" However, criticizing her role and personality, Bosely opined, \"As a consequence, the situation in which they are mutually involved have the constraint and immobility of panel-expressed episodes. When Mr. Disney tries to make them behave like human beings, they're banal.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=990CE6DC1238E532A25750C2A9649C946192D6CF&partner=Rotten%2520Tomatoes|title = Cinderella (1950) THE SCREEN: SIX NEWCOMERS MARK HOLIDAY; Capitol's 'Malaya' Has Tracy and Stewart in Leads-- Two Imports Offered Walt Disney's Feature-Length 'Cinderella,' at the Mayfair, Heads List of Arrivals At the Capitol At the Criterion At the Rialto At the Palace At 55th St. Playhouse|website = The New York Times|first = Bosely|last = Crowther|date = February 23, 1950|accessdate = March 28, 2014|publisher = The New York Times Company}}</ref>\n\n[[Film4]] negatively described Cinderella as \"[[Flat character|one-dimensional]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.film4.com/reviews/1950/cinderella|title = Cinderella|publisher = Channel 4|website = Film4|accessdate = March 28, 2014}}</ref> Criticizing her design, [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]] ''wrote, \"If there is an obvious difference between ''Cinderella'' and such predecessors as ''[[Pinocchio (1940 film)|Pinocchio]]'' and ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White]]'', it's in the general smoothing-out of the character's appearances,\" concluding, \"[[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]] herself looked fairly bland, but the other characters in the first decade of Disney animation had a lot of personality in their faces. They were allowed to look odd. ''Cinderella'' seems to come right out of its time, the bland postwar 1950s,\" likening the character's flawless design to that of a \"[[Draw Me a Map|Draw Me girl]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/cinderella-1987|title = Cinderella|publisher = Ebert Digital LLC|website = Roger Ebert|date = November 20, 1987|accessdate = March 28, 2014|first = Roger|last = Ebert}}</ref> Concerned about the negative effects Cinderella's passivity could possibly induce upon children, Nell Minow of [[Common Sense Media]] expressed, \"Cinderella is the quintessential passive heroine rescued by a male character ... so discussions about her meekness might be in order.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.commonsensemedia.org/movie-reviews/cinderella|title = Cinderella|website = Common Sense Media|accessdate = March 28, 2014|publisher = Common Sense Media Inc|date = October 31, 2005|last = Minow|first = Nell}}</ref> [[About.com]]'s Laurie Boeder simply described Cinderella as \"blah.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://classicfilm.about.com/od/childrensmovies/tp/Disney_Animated_Films_1950s.htm|title = Classic Disney Animated Movies of the 1950s|accessdate = April 15, 2014|website = About.com|publisher = About.com|last = Boeder|first = Laurie}}</ref> Desi Jedeikin of [[Smosh.com|Smosh]] included the character in the website's \"8 Fictional Characters That Are Horrible Role Models For Girls\" list, explaining, \"I'm like so happy that Cinderella found true love with a rich stranger who rescued her from her horrible life. But wouldn't it have been better if she did it for herself?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.smosh.com/smosh-pit/articles/8-fictional-characters-are-horrible-role-models-girls|title = 8 Fictional Characters That Are Horrible Role Models For Girls|publisher = Defy Media, LLC|year = 2011|website = Smosh|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Jedeikin|first = Desi}}</ref> Additionally, critics have also expressed favoritism towards ''Cinderella''<nowiki/>'s [[Supporting Characters|supporting cast]] of [[Anthropomorphism|animal characters]], particularly the comic interaction and dynamic between her pet mice [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Jaq and Gus|Jaq and Gus]] and her stepfamily's pet cat [[Lucifer (Cinderella)|Lucifer]], often preferring them to Cinderella herself while noting ways in which the heroine is constantly being \"upstaged.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/8081/|title = Cinderella (1950) \u2013 In Her Shoes|website = Combustible Celluloid|publisher = Jeffrey M. Anderson|accessdate = March 28, 2014|last = Anderson|first = Jeffrey M.}}</ref>\n\nAmong, Cinderella's positive reviews, Michael Scheinfeld of ''[[TV Guide]] ''drew similarities between the character and [[Belle (Disney)|Belle]] from ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]] ''(1991), writing, ''[[Cinderella]]'' holds up better because the heroine seems timeless in her courage and resourcefulness, a closer cousin to Belle in Disney's ''Beauty and the Beast'' than to other fairytale protagonists.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://movies.tvguide.com/cinderella/review/110901|title = Cinderella|website = TV Guide|accessdate = March 28, 2014|publisher = CBS Interactive Inc|last = Scheinfeld|first = Michael}}</ref> Hailing Cinderella as \"the most famous and beloved princess of all time,\" [[HowStuffWorks]]' Vicki Arkoff defended the character, writing, \"highly sympathetic Cinderella is endlessly kind, patient, hard-working, and unassuming -- no matter how cruelly she is treated by her exaggerated, cartoonish foes.\" Arkoff elaborated, \"Unlike Disney's passive, naive Snow White, Disney's Cinderella is a princess who decides to take charge and change her life for the better, rather than just wait for things to happen that might solve her problem.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://lifestyle.howstuffworks.com/family/activities/movie-fun-night/how-disney-princess-works3.htm|title = Ultimate Guide to Disney Princess|publisher = HowStuffWorks, Inc|website = HowStuffWorks|accessdate = March 31, 2014|last = Arkoff|first = Vicki}}</ref> [[Review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]]' general consensus reads that, in addition to \"The rich colors, sweet songs, adorable mice,\" the \"endearing (if suffering) heroine make[s] ''Cinderella'' a nostalgically lovely charmer.\"<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nWoods herself has collected widespread acclaim for her performance. ''Variety ''wrote, \"Ilene Woods, as Cinderella\u2019s voice, uses a sweet [[soprano]].\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Craig Butler of [[AllMovie]] opined, \"[[Ilene Woods]] makes a marvelous Cinderella, her voice a combination of girlishness and sophistication; she also possesses a serenity and assurance which makes one feel she is more in control of her life than might be guessed by her surroundings.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.allmovie.com/movie/cinderella-v9656/review|title = Cinderella (1950)|accessdate = March 31, 2014|website = AllMovie|first = Craig|last = Butler|publisher = All Media Network, LLC}}</ref> At the time of Woods' death, animation critic and historian Charles Solomon told the ''Los Angeles Times'', \"one of the things about her performance is the warmth she gave the character. As soon as she began to speak, her voice meshed with Marc Davis' animation to create a heroine you liked instantly.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/03/local/la-me-ilene-woods-20100703|title = \nIlene Woods dies at 81; voice of Disney's Cinderella|accessdate = September 23, 2017|website = latimes.com|first = Dennis |last = McLellan|publisher = Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\n[[Lily James]]' portrayal as Cinderella in the [[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|live-action film adaptation]] was generally well-received by critics. [[Joe Morgenstern]] of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' commended James for her performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/cinderella-review-finds-new-soul-in-old-shoe-1426187867|title=\u2018Cinderella\u2019 Review: Finding New Soul in Old Shoe|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Morgenstern, Joe|date=March 12, 2015|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Betsy Sharkey wrote that James makes the character \"seem as if the sweet and spirited young maiden is infused with an inner glow.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-cinderella-20150313-column.html?|title=In 'Cinderella,' no sly asides. Goodness and romance rule|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Sharkey, Betsy|date=March 12, 2015|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref> [[Richard Corliss]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' said that James created a version of the character that is \"both classic and modern.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3743894/cinderella-review-disney-live-action/|title=REVIEW: Disney\u2019s Live-Action Cinderella Rekindles Old Studio Magic|author=Corliss, Richard|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=March 13, 2015|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref>  Lawrence Toppman of ''[[The Charlotte Observer]]'' wrote that James played the character, \"with the right mixture of composure and pluck.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/ent-columns-blogs/lawrence-toppman/article13485305.html|title=Movie review: Sumptuous, subtle ''Cinderella'' satisfies in every way|work=The Charlotte Observer|author=Toppman, Lawrence|date=March 11, 2015|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''{{'}}s David Rooney wrote that James brought \"unaffected sweetness\" to the role and also had \"lovely chemistry\" with her co-star [[Richard Madden]], who played the Prince.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/entry/view/id/914145|title = 'Cinderella': Berlin Review|author =Rooney, David|work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date = February 14, 2015|accessdate = February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nCinderella has since become one of the most famous, recognizable and popular princesses, both fictional and non-fictional, of all-time.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://goarticles.com/article/10-Most-Famous-Fictional-Princesses-of-All-Time/2148070/|title = 10 Most Famous Fictional Princesses of All Time|publisher = GoArticles.com|accessdate = March 29, 2014|website = GoArticles.com|last = Bach|first = Kimberly|date = November 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://listphobia.com/2009/12/09/10-most-famous-fictional-princess-of-all-time/|title = 10 Most Famous Fictional Princess of all Time|publisher =|accessdate = March 29, 2014|website = Listphobia}}</ref> According to the ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'', Cinderella is one of the ten most famous princesses of all-time.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.mysanantonio.com/list/article/10-most-famous-fictional-princesses-1402261.php|title = 10 most famous fictional princesses|date = May 30, 2011|accessdate = March 29, 2014|website = San Antonio Express-News|publisher = [[Hearst Newspapers, LLC]]}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]] ''ranked the character the ninth greatest Disney Princess.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cosmopolitan.com/sex-love/advice/disney-princesses-ranked|title = The Definitive Ranking of Disney Princesses|publisher = Hearst Communications, Inc|website = Cosmopolitan|accessdate = March 29, 2014|last = Breslaw|first = Anna|date = December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 Woods received a [[Disney Legends]] award for her role as the voice of Cinderella. In 2010 she died at the age of 81, of [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2010/07/07/ilene-woods-voice-of-disneys-cinderella-dies-at-81|title = Ilene Woods, Voice Of Disney's Cinderella, Dies At 81|website = LA Weekly|publisher = LA Weekly, LP|accessdate = March 29, 2014|date = July 7, 2010|last = Wei|first = Clarissa}}</ref> According to ''[[The Spokesman-Review]]'', Woods once said in an interview with ''[[Starlog]] ''that \"I love the idea that after I\u2019m gone, children will still be hearing my voice [as Cinderella].\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2010/jul/04/ilene-woods-voice-of-disneys-cinderella/|title = Ilene Woods, voice of Disney\u2019s Cinderella|website = The Spokesman-Review|publisher = The Spokesman-Review|accessdate = March 29, 2014|date = July 4, 2010}}</ref> In 2013, [[Film School Rejects]] recognized Woods as one of \"7 No-Name Actors Who Had Iconic Roles\", ranking the actress first and writing, \"Woods ... really set the bar high, as she managed to audition for the part of Cinderella without even realize she had done it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://filmschoolrejects.com/cinematic-listology/7-no-name-actors-who-had-iconic-roles.php|title = 7 No-Name Actors Who Had Iconic Roles|website = Film School Rejects|date = October 2, 2013|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = Reject Media, LLC|last = Bell|first = David Christopher}}</ref>\n\n[[Lily James]]' performance as Cinderella in the [[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|2015 live-action film]] earned her nominations for the [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Sci-Fi/Fantasy]] and the award for \"Favorite Movie Actress\" at the [[2016 Kids' Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kids' Choice Awards: Adele, Justin Bieber, 'Star Wars' Among Nominees|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kids-choice-awards-adele-justin-861147|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/teen-choice-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201571268/ Teen Choice Awards 2015 Winners: Full List] ''Variety'', Retrieved April 17, 2017</ref> She also won the 2015 Breakthrough Award at the Harper's Bazaar Women of the Year Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcarpet-fashionawards.com/2015/11/04/lily-james-in-erdem-2015-harpers-bazaar-women-of-the-year-awards/|title=Lily James In Erdem \u2013 2015 Harper\u2019s Bazaar Women of the Year Awards|first=Catherine|last=Kallon|date=4 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208153455/http://www.redcarpet-fashionawards.com/2015/11/04/lily-james-in-erdem-2015-harpers-bazaar-women-of-the-year-awards/|archivedate=8 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Cultural impact===\nCulturally, Cinderella has had a profound influence on the [[fashion industry]]. According to Sarah Osman of [[Young Hollywood]], \"Cinderella\u2019s gown in this film is so iconic that it's become canon that Cinderella wears a light blue dress to the ball.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.younghollywood.com/scene/the-5-best-cinderella-film-adaptations.html|title = The 5 Best Cinderella Film Adaptations!|date = |accessdate = September 12, 2015|website = Young Hollywood|publisher = Young Hollywood LLC|last = Osman|first = Sarah}}</ref> To coincide with the release of the diamond edition of ''Cinderella ''in 2012, French footwear designer [[Christian Louboutin]] created and designed a contemporary rendition of the character's iconic glass slipper. In an interview with ''The Express Tribune'', Louboutin said that Cinderella is \"not only an iconic character when it comes to beauty, grace and fairytale love, but also shoes.\" The shoes are described as \"made of delicate lace [instead of glass] to give them a look of transparency, and adorned with butterfly designs at the vamp and atop the Swarovski-crystal covered heel,\" completed by Louboutin\u2019s signature red soles. Only twenty copies of the shoes were manufactured.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://tribune.com.pk/story/404613/christian-louboutins-cinderella-slipper-makes-fairytale-come-true/|title = Christian Louboutin\u2019s Cinderella slipper makes fairytale come true|website = The Express Tribune|publisher = The Express Tribune News Network|date = July 7, 2012|accessdate = March 29, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]] ''ranked Cinderella tenth in its article \"Disney Princesses: Ranking Their Hairdos -- and Don'ts!\", writing, \"The lowly maid's typically rage-inducing bangs somehow develop an almost stately character once the rest of her follicular baggage has been swept into an updo closely resembling a perky butt.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20609151_20445104_20880962,00.html#20880960|title = Disney Princesses: Ranking Their Hairdos -- and Don'ts!|date = March 27, 2014|website = Entertainment Weekly|publisher = Entertainment Weekly Inc|accessdate = March 29, 2014|last = Barrett|first = Annie}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[86th Academy Awards]] in 2014, Kenyan actress and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] recipient [[Lupita Nyong'o]] donned \"a light blue [[Prada]] gown.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.popsugar.com/Lupita-Nyongo-Looks-Like-Cinderella-Oscars-2014-34230698|title = Lupita Nyong'o Looks Just Like Cinderella at the Oscars|date = March 2, 2014|website = PopSugar|publisher = POPSUGAR Inc|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Whitney|first = Alyse}}</ref> Subsequently, the media responded by drawing similarities between Nyong'o's dress and Cinderella's [[ballgown]]. ''Cosmopolitan ''wrote that Nyong'o \"took a cue from Disney with a blue iridescent gown and matching headband ''[[a la]]'' Cinderella,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/news/lupita-nyongo-oscars|title = Lupita Nyong'o Is In A Cinderella Gown At The Oscars|publisher = Hearst Communications, Inc|website = Cosmopolitan|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Breslaw|first = Anna|date = March 2, 2014}}</ref> while the ''[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] ''similarly opined \"channeled another Disney princess for her Oscars gown.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/oscars/lupita-nyong-channels-cinderella-oscars-gown-article-1.1708787|title = Oscars 2014: Lupita Nyong\u2019o\u2019s powder blue princess gown draws comparison to Cinderella|publisher = NYDailyNews.com|website = Daily News|accessdate = March 30, 2014|date = March 3, 2014|last = Monde|first = Chiderah}}</ref> Acknowledging the comparisons, Nyong'o's stylist Micaela Erlanger described the actress' appearance as \"Lupita + Cinderella = Lupitarella.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-fashion-2014-lupita-nyongo-685120|title = Oscars Fashion: Lupita Nyong'o Sparkles in a Fred Leighton Headband|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = The Hollywood Reporter|website = The Hollywood Reporter|last = Chan|first = Stephanie|date = March 2, 2014}}</ref> Additionally, several critics have deemed Nyong'o's success a \"Cinderella story.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.hitfix.com/in-contention/12-years-a-slave-star-lupita-nyongo-holds-off-jennifer-lawrence-to-win-the-best-supporting-actress-oscar|title = '12 Years a Slave' star Lupita Nyong'o holds off Jennifer Lawrence to win the Best Supporting Actress Oscar|publisher = HitFix, Inc|date = March 2, 2014|accessdate = March 30, 2014|website = HitFix|last = Tapley|first = Kristopher}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cnn.com/2014/03/03/opinion/davis-lupita-nyongo/|title = Lupita, a Cinderella for everybody|website = CNN|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = Cable News Network|last = Davis|first = Michaela Angela|date = March 3, 2014}}</ref> According to [[MTV]], several other Academy Award attendants wore similar outfits that were reminiscent of Disney characters in addition to Nyong'o.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1723322/oscars-2014-red-carpet-disney-princesses.jhtml|title = Why Is Everyone At The Oscars Dressed Like Disney Characters?|website = MTV|publisher = Viacom International Inc|date = Mar 2, 2014|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Zalben|first = Alex}}</ref>\n\n====Makeover sequence====\nThe iconic \"[[Bibbidi-Bobbidi-Boo]]\" [[Number (music)|musical sequence]] in which Cinderella's Fairy Godmother magically transforms the character's tattered rags into a beautiful ball gown has garnered widespread critical acclaim, receiving positive reviews, accolades and recognition from several entertainment critics. AllMovie described the sequence as \"splendidly done,\"<ref name=\":3\" /> while HitFix deemed it the film's best moment.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.hitfix.com/galleries/overlay/top-20-disney-animated-films-of-all-time|title = Top 20 Disney Animated Films of All-Time|website = HitFix|publisher = HitFix, Inc|date = November 25, 2013|accessdate = April 16, 2014|last = Lasser|first = Josh}}</ref> According to [[Disney.com]], the transformation of Cinderella's dress into a ballgown remains a common favorite and \"one of the most iconic pieces of Disney animation because of what it means for the titular character.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogs.disney.com/disney-style/fashion/2014/05/14/the-best-disney-style-moments-of-transformation/|title = The Best Disney Style Moments of Transformation|date = May 15, 2014|accessdate = May 17, 2014|website = Official Disney Blogs|publisher = Disney|last =|first =}}</ref> StyleCaster wrote that the scene is responsible for introducing the common \"movie makeover,\" writing, \"Ever since Cinderella ditched those rags and threw on a ball gown and a pair of glass slippers, movie audiences have fallen for the beloved transformation storyline.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.stylecaster.com/10-amazing-movie-makeovers-devil-wears-prada-girls/|title = 10 Amazing Movie Makeovers, From \"The Devil Wears Prada\" to \"Mean Girls\"|website = StyleCaster|publisher = StyleCaster INC|accessdate = March 28, 2014|date = November 27, 2012|last = Cain|first = Spencer}}</ref> Featuring Cinderella in its list of \"13 movie makeovers that still totally rock our socks off\", ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] ''summarized the scene's role in the film as \"The movie makeover that sees a merry band of rodents help Cindera[''sic'']lla to make the perfect dress, eventually go to the ball and ultimately win the heart of a prince.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/news/features/2013/10/brilliant-movie-makeovers-sandy-grease-cinderella-pretty-woman|title = 13 movie makeovers that still totally rock our socks off|website = Glamour|publisher = Nast UK|date = October 11, 2013|last = Powell|first = Hannah Lyons|accessdate = March 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Oprah.com]] also included Cinderella in its \"Favorite Movie Makeovers\" list, accrediting the film and Disney with \"first introducing us to the head-to-toe makeover,\" concluding, \" Unrealistic expectations are born.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.oprah.com/entertainment/Screening-Room-Favorite-Movie-Makeovers|title = Favorite Movie Makeovers|date = April 27, 2009|website = Oprah.com|publisher = Harpo Productions, Inc|accessdate = March 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLikewise, both the sequence and Cinderella's magical transformation have been featured on several \"best movie makeover\" [[countdown]] lists. On ''[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]]''<nowiki/>'s list of the \"50 Best Movie Makeovers\", Cinderella placed first, with the magazine labeling her the \"Recipient of the original makeover.\" Additionally, ''Stylist'' coined the list's other candidates \"Cinematic Cinderellas,\" alluding to the character's legacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.stylist.co.uk/beauty/50-best-movie-makeovers#item-50|title = 50 Best Movie Makeovers|date = April 24, 2013|website = Stylist|publisher = Stylist|accessdate = March 29, 2014}}</ref> ''[[InStyle]]'' ranked ''Cinderella ''second on its list of \"The Best Movie Makeovers\", writing, \"Cinderella\u2019s fairy tale transformation is the stuff that many a little girl's real-life makeover dreams are made of.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.instyle.com/instyle/package/general/photos/0,,20542054_20572501_21088407,00.html|title = The Best Movie Makeovers \u2013 Cinderella (1950)|accessdate = March 29, 2014|website = InStyle}}</ref> Hailing it as \"[The] makeover of makeovers\" and \"the movie that started it all,\" ''[[The Independent Florida Alligator]]'' ranked ''Cinderella ''first in its list of \"The best of movie makeovers\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.alligator.org/blogs/thursday/article_694a3c88-d483-11e2-acb1-001a4bcf887a.html|title = The best of movie makeovers|website = The Independent Florida Alligator|publisher = The Independent Florida Alligator|date = June 13, 2013|last = Champalanne|first = Michelle|accessdate = March 29, 2014}}</ref> Style Blazer also ranked ''Cinderella'' second on its list of the \"Top 11 Favorite Makeover Movies of All Time\", concluding, \"Cinderella and her pauper to princess makeover have already gone down in movie history as one of the best transformations.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://styleblazer.com/58275/top-11-favorite-makeover-movies-of-all-time-see-which-ones-made-our-list/10/|title = Top 11 Favorite Makeover Movies of All Time (See Which Ones Made Our List!)|website = Style Blazer|publisher = Moguldom Media Group|date = June 18, 2012|accessdate = March 28, 2014|last = Lawrence|first = Tameika}}</ref> Calling Cinderella the \"Original Fairy Godmother ... makeover,\" ''[[Total Beauty Media|Total Beauty]] ''ranked the character fifth in its article \"11 Best Movie Makeovers\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.totalbeauty.com/content/slideshows/11-best-movie-makeovers/page5|title = 11 Best Movie Makeovers|website = Total Beauty|date = July 22, 2013|publisher = Total Beauty Media, Inc|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Glick|first = Lila}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Disney}}\n{{commons category|Cinderella (Disney character)}}\n*[http://princess.disney.com/cinderella Cinderella] at [http://princess.disney.com/ Disney Princess]\n\n{{Disney's Cinderella}}\n{{Disney Princess}}\n{{Cinderella (Fairy tale)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cinderella (Disney Character)}}\n[[Category:Cinderella (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Cinderella characters]]\n[[Category:Disney Princess characters]]\n[[Category:Kingdom Hearts characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional maids]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 1950]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox character \n| colour             = #BCD4E6\n| name               = Cinderella\n| series             = [[Cinderella (franchise)|Cinderella]]\n| image              = [[File:Cinderella disney.png|200px]]\n| caption            = Cinderella as she appears in Disney's ''[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]''.\n| first              = ''[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]'' (1950)\n| last               = \n| creator            = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Charles Perrault]]\n*[[Marc Davis (animator)|Marc Davis]]\n*[[Eric Larson]]\n*[[Les Clark]]\n*[[Mark Henn]]\n*[[Walt Disney]]}}\n| lbl1               = Based on\n| data1              = Cinderella from the [[Charles Perrault]]'s [[Cinderella|fairy tale]]\n| portrayer          = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Lily James]]<br> ([[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|2015 film]])<br>Eloise Webb {{small|(child)}}<br>([[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|2015 film]])}}\n| voice              = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Ilene Woods]]<br>([[Cinderella (1950 film)|1950 film]])\n*[[Kath Soucie]]<br>(''[[Walt Disney Parks and Resorts|Disney Parks]]'')\n*Tami Tappan<br>(singing in ''[[Cinderella III: A Twist in Time|Cinderella III]]'')\n*[[Karen Strassman]]<br>(''[[Mickey Mouse (TV series)|Mickey Mouse]]'')\n*Susan Stevens Logan<br>(studio singing voice)\n*[[Jennifer Hale]]<br><small>(2001\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| species            = <!-- if not obvious -->\n| gender             = <!-- if not obvious -->\n| occupation         = [[Scullery maid]]\n| title              = Princess\n| affiliation        = [[Disney Princess]]\n| family             = {{Plainlist|\n*Father (dies in prologue)\n*[[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Lady Tremaine|Lady Tremaine]] (stepmother)\n*[[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Drizella Tremaine|Drizella]] and [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Anastasia Tremaine|Anastasia]] Tremaine (stepsisters)\n*The Baker (step-brother-in-law)\n*The King (father-in-law)}}\n| spouse             = [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Prince Charming|Prince Charming]]\n| children           = Chad Charming (Descendants)\n| nationality        = \n}}\n'''Cinderella''' is a fictional character who appears in [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Productions]]' 12th animated feature film ''[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]'' (1950) and its [[sequel]]s ''[[Cinderella II: Dreams Come True]]'' (2002) and ''[[Cinderella III: A Twist in Time]]'' (2007). In the original film, Cinderella is voiced by American singer and actress [[Ilene Woods]]. For the sequels and subsequent film and television appearances, Woods was replaced by American actresses [[Jennifer Hale]] and Tami Tappan, who provide the character's speaking and singing voices respectively. \n\nIn the wake of her father's untimely demise, Cinderella is left in the unfortunate care of her cruel stepmother and jealous stepsisters, who constantly mistreat her, forcing Cinderella to work as a [[scullery maid]] in her own home. When Prince Charming holds a ball, the evil stepmother does not allow her to go. Cinderella, aided by her kind Fairy Godmother and equipped with a beautiful silver gown and a unique pair of glass slippers, attends, only to have to leave at [[midnight]] when the Fairy Godmother's spell is broken.\n\nReception towards Cinderella has been mixed, with some film critics describing the character as much too passive, [[Flat character|one-dimensional]], and less interesting than the film's supporting characters. Other critics found her endearing, charming, and timeless. Woods' vocal performance has also been praised. Panned or praised, Cinderella has nonetheless become one of the most famous and recognizable princesses in the history of film. With her iconic glass slippers, silver gown, hairstyle, and transformation, one of the first on-screen makeovers of its kind, the character has been established as a fashion icon, receiving accolades and recognition from ''InStyle'', ''Entertainment Weekly'', ''Glamour'' and ''Oprah.com'', as well as footwear designer and fashion icon [[Christian Louboutin]], who, in 2012, designed and released a shoe based on Cinderella's glass slippers. [[Lily James]] played a live-action version of the character in the [[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|2015 live action adaptation]] of the original 1950 film.\n\n==Development==\nThe Disney version of Cinderella was based on the French version of the tale by [[Charles Perrault]], ''Cendrillon'' written in 1697 in ''Histoires ou Contes du Temps Pass\u00e9''.<ref name=\"masterworks\">{{cite web|work=Disney Archives|title=Walt's Masterworks: Cinderella|url=http://disney.go.com/disneyatoz/familymuseum/collection/masterworks/cinderella/index.html}}</ref>\n\n===Personality===\nThe script for the original film went through revisions by various writers, sometimes with different interpretations of the character. [[Maurice Rapf]] tried to make her a less passive character than [[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]], and more rebellious against her stepfamily. Rapf explained, \"My thinking was you can't have somebody who comes in and changes everything for you. You can't be delivered it on a platter. You've got to earn it. So in my version, the Fairy Godmother said, 'It's okay till midnight but from then on it's up to you.' I made her earn it, and what she had to do to achieve it was to rebel against her stepmother and stepsisters, to stop being a slave in her own home. So I had a scene where they're ordering her around and she throws the stuff back at them. She revolts, so they lock her up in the attic. I don't think anyone took (my idea) very seriously.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Mouse Under Glass: Secrets of Disney Animation & Theme Parks|last=Koenig|first=David|publisher=Bonaventure Press|year=1997|isbn=978-0964060517|location=|pages=75}}</ref>\n\n===Appearance===\nThe character was animated by [[Marc Davis (animator)|Marc Davis]] and [[Eric Larson]],<ref>{{cite book|author=Pierre Lambert|title=Walt Disney, l'\u00e2ge d'or|page=166|isbn=2950781888}}</ref> but the two animators did not have the same perception of the character, accentuating the elegance of [[Marc Davis (animator)|Davis]] and [[Eric Larson|Larson]]'s opting for simplicity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Pierre Lambert|title=Walt Disney, l'\u00e2ge d'or|page=167|isbn=2950781888}}</ref> As done with other Disney films, [[Walt Disney]] hired actress [[Helene Stanley]] to perform the live-action reference for Cinderella, that she before artists began sketching, playing the role of Cinderella in a particular scene,<ref>{{cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of Walt Disney's Animated Characters|author=John Grant|isbn=0060157771|page=228}}</ref> and artists to draw animated frames based on the movements of the actress.<ref name=\"archives\" /> She later did the same kind of work for the characters of [[Aurora (Disney)|Princess Aurora]] in ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]'' and Anita Radcliff in ''[[One Hundred and One Dalmatians|101 Dalmatians]]''.<ref name=\"archives\">{{cite web|work=Disney Archives|title=Cinderella Character History|url=http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/characters/cinderella/cinderella.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331190207/http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/characters/cinderella/cinderella.html|archivedate=2010-03-31}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Christopher Finch, author of ''The Art of Walt Disney'':{{cquote|Disney insisted that all scenes involving human characters should be shot first in live-action to determine that they would work before the expensive business of animation was permitted to start. The animators did not like this way of working, feeling it detracted from their ability to create character. However, they understood the necessity for this approach in retrospect and acknowledged that Disney had handled things with considerable subtlety.<ref name=masterworks />}}\n\n===Voice===\nIn the original 1950 film, Cinderella is voiced by American singer and actress [[Ilene Woods]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.chron.com/life/style/gallery/Disney-princesses-and-the-real-voices-behind-them-72151/photo-5324428.php|title = Disney princesses and the real voices behind them|publisher = [[Hearst Newspapers, LLC]]|website = The Houston Chronicle|accessdate = March 30, 2014}}</ref> In 1948, Woods was a young eighteen-year-old singer working as a radio personality at the time and hosting her own [[eponymous]] [[radio program]] ''The Ilene Woods Show''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2010/jul/19/ilene-woods-obituary|title = Ilene Woods obituary|publisher = Guardian News and Media Limited|website = The Guardian|accessdate = March 30, 2014|date = July 19, 2010|last = Sibley|first = Brian}}</ref> While working at [[ABC Radio Network|ABC Radio]],<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://news.moviefone.ca/2010/07/02/ilene-woods-cinderella-dead-at-81/|title = Ilene Woods, Voice of Disney's 'Cinderella,' Dead at 81|website = Moviefone|publisher = Aol Inc|last = Harris|first = Scott|date = July 2, 2010|accessdate = March 30, 2014}}</ref> Woods would regularly be visited and approached by various songwriters who wanted the singer to perform their compositions, which is ultimately how she met and befriended ''Cinderella ''songwriters [[Mack David]] and [[Jerry Livingston]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=67494|title = Ilene Woods, the Voice of Cinderella, Has Passed Away|website = ComingSoon.net|date = July 2, 2010|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = CraveOnline Media, LLC}}</ref> Ultimately, David and Livingston \"would play ... an important role in Woods's career.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAt the behest of David and Livingston, casually described as \"a favor\",<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/ilene-woods-voice-of-cinderella-dies-1.911803|title = Ilene Woods, voice of Cinderella, dies|website = CBC|publisher = CBC 2014|date = July 4, 2010|accessdate = March 30, 2014}}</ref> Woods agreed to record a series of demos of three songs that the songwriters had recently written for the studio's then-upcoming animated film ''Cinderella''. Woods'' ''recorded the songs \"[[Bibbidi-Bobbidi-Boo]]\", \"So This Is Love\", and \"[[A Dream Is a Wish Your Heart Makes]]\",<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.fosters.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100704/GJNEWS02/707049934/0/citrss2|title = Ilene Woods, N.H.-born voice of Cinderella, dies at 81|date = July 4, 2010|website = Fosters.com|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = Geo. J. Foster Company|last = Reino|first = Roni}}</ref> which the songwriters then submitted to Disney himself. Upon reviewing and listening to the tracks, Disney, impressed, decided to contact Woods personally. Two days afterward, Woods received a telephone call from Disney, with whom she immediately scheduled an interview. Woods recalled in an interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', \"We met and talked for awhile, and he said, 'How would you like to be Cinderella?'\", to which she agreed.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/03/local/la-me-ilene-woods-20100703|title = Ilene Woods dies at 81; voice of Disney's Cinderella|date = July 3, 2010|accessdate = March 30, 2014|website = Los Angeles Times|publisher = Los Angeles Times|last = McLellan|first = Dennis}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nCinderella is 19 years old with medium-length strawberry-blonde hair, blue eyes, and fair complexion. After her father dies, she is forced into servitude in her own home and is  tormented by her evil stepmother, [[Lady Tremaine]], and two stepsisters, Anastasia and Drizella. Despite this, she maintains hope through her dreams and remains a kind, gentle and sweet person. She has faith that someday her dreams of happiness will come true and her kindness will be repaid. Cinderella is shown to have a down-to-earth attitude, but she is also a daydreamer.  For example, in \"Sing Sweet Nightingale\", she becomes distracted with the bubbles, allowing Lucifer to smudge the floor she was cleaning.  Also, after hearing that the Grand Duke is traveling the kingdom with the missing slipper, she dreamily dances back to the attic humming the song she heard at the ball. She is also shown to have a sarcastic side and a sharp wit.\n\nWith the help of her animal friends, she fixes up an old party dress of her mother's so she can attend a royal ball.  However, when her evil stepsisters brutally tear the dress apart, she is heartbroken and fears that her dreams will never come true until her [[Fairy Godmother]] appears, restoring Cinderella's hope by transforming her torn homemade dress into her now-iconic silver [[ball gown|gown]] with a glittering crystalline puffed peplum, a delicate laced white [[petticoat]], and puffy sleeves. Her hair is worn up in a [[French twist (hairstyle)|French twist]] supported by a silver headband with diamond earrings, silver-white opera gloves, a black diamond choker, and glass slippers.\n\nHer look was probably inspired by 1950s French haute couture, while her torn dress is clearly inspired by Salvador Dal\u00ec and Elsa Schiaparelli's Tear dress.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lugli|first1=Emanuele|title=Tear That Dress: Cinderella (1950) and Disney's Critique of Postwar Fashion|url=http://brightlightsfilm.com/tear-that-dress-off-cinderella-1950-and-disneys-critique-of-postwar-fashion/#.VeWdKtO6feR|website=Bright Lights Film Journal|accessdate=2015-08-31}}</ref>\n\nAs a servant, she wears her hair down in a ponytail, held in place with a blue ribbon, sometimes supported by a white scarf and wears a brown dress with a powder blue blouse, a white apron, and black flats.\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===''Cinderella''===\n{{main|Cinderella (1950 film)}}\n[[File:Disneyland Cinderella handstogether.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Cinderella as she appears at [[Disney Parks]].]]\nAt the start of the film, the titular character Cinderella is working as a scullery maid in her own home for her cruel stepmother named Lady Tremaine and her two stepsisters named Anastasia and Drizella. Her only friends are the birds, the mice who also live in the [[manor]], including [[Gus and Jaq]], her pet dog Bruno and her father's horse Major.\n\nShe prepares breakfast for the animals and for her stepfamily before beginning her regular chores. An invitation to the ball arrives at the door and Cinderella wants to attend. Her stepmother tells her she may go under the condition that she must finish her chores and find something suitable to wear. Cinderella discovers her deceased mother's old party dress and hopes to fix it to make it more modern, but she is too busy to do so. Meanwhile, when the mice see shadows of Cinderella's stepsisters throwing down their old sash and beads, Jaq and Gus are forced to quietly retrieve them. The mice use the unwanted items to fix up the dress. Later, Cinderella fears she will not be done working in time and will not be able to attend the ball, but her friends reveal the altered dress. Cinderella is overjoyed and thanks her friends. She races down the steps just in time, but her stepsisters recognize their discarded items and accuse her of stealing their sash and beads. They tear the dress to shreds, leaving Cinderella all by herself, and she runs out to the garden, crying.\n\nHer [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Fairy Godmother|Fairy Godmother]] appears to make her dreams come true and transforms her torn dress into a beautiful shimmering silver gown. Before Cinderella leaves, her godmother warns her that the spell will be broken at midnight. At the ball, Cinderella dances with Prince Charming and they immediately fall in love with each other. As twelve o'clock approaches, she hurries to leave, hoping to prevent the spell from breaking at the ball, which could cause her to get caught by her stepmother or stepsisters. In her haste, she loses one of her glass slippers on the staircase but fails to retrieve it in time. Cinderella hurries into her coach as it prepares to leave. The spell breaks and Cinderella is in rags once more before reminiscing her dance with the prince and thanking her godmother for all she's done for her. The next day, the prince announces he will marry the maiden whose foot fits into the glass slipper. Lady Tremaine hears Cinderella humming the same song that had played at the ball and figures out Cinderella was the girl Prince Charming fell in love with. Cinderella is locked in the tower by her stepmother, who refuses to let her have the opportunity to try on the slipper, but her animal friends help her escape. She hurries downstairs to try on the glass slipper. Knowing the slipper will fit her, Lady Tremaine intentionally causes the footman to trip and shatter the slipper. Cinderella reveals that she has kept the other slipper. She tries it on, and it fits perfectly. She and the Prince are married soon after.<ref name=\"Film\">{{cite video|people=Wilfred Jackson (director)|title=[[Cinderella (1950 film)|Cinderella]]|publisher=[[Walt Disney]]|date=1950}}</ref>\n\n===''Cinderella II: Dreams Come True''===\n{{main|Cinderella II: Dreams Come True}}\nGus and Jaq, with help of the other mice, and the Fairy Godmother, set off to make a new book to narrate what happens after the ending of the previous story by stringing three segments of stories together, resulting in three individual stories: \"Aim to Please\", \"Tall Tail\", and \"An Uncommon Romance\". In the first story, Cinderella and Prince Charming return home and a party begins shortly afterward. In the second story, \"Tall Tail\", Cinderella works on planning to build up a festival. The mouse named Jaq in the previous film has become a human named Sir Hugh. And in the third story, \"An Uncommon Romance\", Cinderella helps her younger stepsister [[Anastasia Tremaine|Anastasia]] reconcile with the baker, even though her stepmother Lady Tremaine has forbidden it. Near the end of the film, she reads the book that the mice made for her.<ref>{{cite video|people=John Kafka (director)|title=[[Cinderella II: Dreams Come True]]|publisher=[[DisneyToon Studios]]|date=2002}}</ref>\n\n===''Cinderella III: A Twist in Time''===\n{{main|Cinderella III: A Twist in Time}}\nIn Cinderella III: A Twist in Time, Cinderella's hard-working ethics, optimism, and devotion are put to the test, when she is magically stripped away from her \"happily ever after\" by a vengeful and then magically-empowered Tremaine and is forced to jump into physical action to restore her happy life and relationship with Prince Charming. During these events, Cinderella is shown to be cunning, tactical, persistent, and a fierce rival to those who oppress her. With no magic, being forced to rely solely on her intelligence and fearlessness, Cinderella is able to defeat her stepmother, repair her relationship with a reformed Anastasia and retain her much-deserved life of happiness, proving both her independence and strong will.<ref>{{cite video|people=Frank Nissen (director)|title=[[Cinderella III: A Twist in Time]]|publisher=[[DisneyToon Studios]]|date=2007}}</ref>\n\n===''Sofia the First''===\n{{main|Sofia the First}}\nCinderella appears in the pilot movie ''[[Sofia the First|Sofia the First: Once Upon a Princess]]'', where she helps Sofia make friends with Amber, her stepsister.\n\n===\"Le Croissant de Triomphe\"===\nIn the newest editions of ''[[Mickey Mouse (TV series)|Mickey Mouse]]'' short movies, a 2013 production reflects the iconic princess in a crucial moment.\n\nCinderella appears in the third episode of ''Mickey Mouse,'' entitled ''[http://video.disney.com/watch/disneychannel-croissant-de-triomphe-4d7b3aae690a98650d776d97 Le Croissant de Triomphe]''. While a cafe owned and operated by [[Minnie Mouse|Minnie]] runs out of [[croissant]]s, she makes a phone call to receive from [[Mickey Mouse|Mickey]] an order of croissants. In order to arrive on time, Mickey hurries and flies through Paris, and accidentally lands in [[Cinderella Castle|a castle]] where [[Prince Charming]] tries to fit the crystal slipper into Cinderella's foot. She was still dressed in her regular maid clothes. At that time, Mickey accidentally passes in his motorcycle and breaks the glass slipper.\n\n===2015 film===\n[[Lily James]] portrays the character, named Ella, in Disney's 2015 live-action version of ''[[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|Cinderella]]''. Like in the original film, her father remarries after the death of her mother but after he dies as well, she then becomes the horribly mistreated servant of her stepmother Lady Tremaine and her two stepsisters, Anastasia and Drisella. They give her the nickname \"Cinderella\" when, one morning, she wakes up with [[Cinder|soot]] on her face after sleeping near the fireplace the previous night. Unlike the original film, however, she meets the Prince (named Kit) before the ball while out in the forest. She is also shown to be more assertive when she actually stands up to her stepmother in the film's final act; Lady Tremaine attempts to blackmail Ella by only agreeing to let her try on the glass slipper if Ella will make her head of the royal household and provide suitable husbands for her stepsisters, but Ella rejects this idea, refusing to give Lady Tremaine power over Kit after the way she ruined Ella's life.\n\n==In other media==\n[[File:Tokyo Disneylands cinderella castle.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Cinderella Castle]] at [[Tokyo Disneyland]].]]\n[[File:Cinderella castle day.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Cinderella Castle]] at [[Walt Disney World]].]]\nCinderella appears as one of the Disney [[Princesses of Heart]] in the ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]'' series, captured by Maleficent, who destroyed her world. The main character, [[Characters of Kingdom Hearts#Sora|Sora]], rescues Cinderella, as well as the other Princesses, and she returns home. She is only mentioned in the sequel, ''[[Kingdom Hearts II]]''. Her story prior to being captured takes place prominently with her home world, Castle of Dreams, in the prequel, ''[[Kingdom Hearts Birth by Sleep]]''; she meets Ventus, who she mistakes for a mouse despite the obvious fact he's not, Aqua and Terra. In the ''Final Mix'' version of the game, her world is seen in the Realm of Darkness at the climax, Maleficent having destroyed it and captured her.\n\nCinderella is one of the official members of the [[Disney Princess]] franchise, appearing in several related video games, albums and other merchandise. Cinderella appears as one of the [[Disney Princess]]es in the manga, [[Kilala Princess]].\n\nCinderella appears in the [[Nintendo 3DS]] game ''[[Disney Magical World]]''. Cinderella's world is one of the four Disney movie worlds accessible to the player in this game, and many characters and items related to the movie appear. Additionally, the player has the option of attending balls at Cinderella's castle.\n\nThe [[Cinderella Castle]] is an attraction at [[Walt Disney World]]'s [[Magic Kingdom]] and [[Tokyo Disneyland]] at the [[Tokyo Disney Resort]]. Both serve as globally recognized icons for their respective theme parks. Cinderella and the other Disney Princesses have a meet and greet attraction called ''Princess Fairytale Hall'' at Magic Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidethemagic.net/2012/04/walt-disney-world-reveals-new-fantasyland-dates-closer-look-at-princess-fairy-tale-hall-be-our-guest-restaurant-and-more/|title=Walt Disney World reveals New Fantasyland dates, closer look at Princess Fairy Tale Hall, Be Our Guest restaurant, and more|work=Inside the Magic|first=Ricky|last=Brigante|date=April 28, 2012|accessdate=April 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.insidethemagic.net/2013/09/princess-fairytale-hall-to-make-royal-debut-on-sept-18-as-walt-disney-world-completes-new-home-for-cinderella-rapunzel/ Princess Fairytale Hall to make royal debut on Sept 18 as Walt Disney World completes new home for Cinderella, Rapunzel] Inside the Magic, Retrieved September 7, 2013</ref>\n\nIn the season six episodes of the sitcom series ''[[Full House]]'' known as ''The House Meets The Mouse Parts 1 & 2'', Cinderella makes cameo appearances in both Parts 1 & 2. She also appears in ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing With the Stars]]'' played by [[Sabrina Bryan]] in season 15, [[Amy Purdy]] in season 18, and [[Witney Carson]] in season 22. [[Jessy Schram]] played a live-action version of the character in ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]'' and its spin-off ''[[Once Upon a Time in Wonderland]]''. [[Dania Ramirez]] portrays another version of the role in season 7 as a main character with a different storyline.\n\nCinderella, alongside other Disney Princesses, appeared in the film ''[[Ralph Breaks the Internet]]'', as was announced at the 2017 D23 Expo.<ref name=\"Princesses2\">{{cite magazine|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/07/14/wreck-it-ralph-sequel-star-wars-disney-princesses/|title=Wreck-It Ralph sequel will unite the Disney princesses \u2014 and Star Wars!|last=Breznican|first=Anthony|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Reception and legacy==\n\n===Critical response===\nAlthough the film has garnered critical acclaim,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1004186-cinderella/|title = Cinderella (1950)|website = Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate = March 29, 2014|publisher = Flixster, Inc}}</ref> Cinderella herself has attracted mostly mixed reviews in modern times.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.decentfilms.com/reviews/cinderella1950|title = Cinderella (1950)|website = Decent Films Guide|publisher = Steven D. Greydanus|accessdate = March 28, 2014|last = Greyandus|first = Steven D.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2009/12/11/best_aamp_worst_disney_princesses|title = Best & Worst Disney Princesses|website = Starpulse.com|accessdate = March 29, 2014|date = December 11, 2009|publisher = Starpulse.com|last = Zanello|first = Michael}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' disliked the character, describing her as \"colorless.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = https://variety.com/1949/film/reviews/cinderella-3-1200416691/|title = Review: \u2018Cinderella\u2019|publisher = Variety Media, LLC|date = December 31, 1949|website = Variety|accessdate = March 28, 2014}}</ref> Calling her an \"oppressed drudge,\" ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] ''panned Cinderella, describing both her and Prince Charming as \"bland and colourless characters - particularly when compared to [[Belle (Disney)|Beauty]] and her [[Beast (Disney)|Beast]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?DVDID=116838|title = Cinderella|website = Empire|publisher = Bauer Consumer Media Ltd|accessdate = March 28, 2014|year = 2009}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]''<nowiki/>' [[Bosley Crowther]] similarly wrote, \"The beautiful Cinderella has a [[voluptuous]] face and form\u2014not to mention an eager disposition\u2014to compare with [[Al Capp]]'s [[Daisy Mae]].\" However, criticizing her role and personality, Bosely opined, \"As a consequence, the situation in which they are mutually involved have the constraint and immobility of panel-expressed episodes. When Mr. Disney tries to make them behave like human beings, they're banal.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=990CE6DC1238E532A25750C2A9649C946192D6CF&partner=Rotten%2520Tomatoes|title = Cinderella (1950) THE SCREEN: SIX NEWCOMERS MARK HOLIDAY; Capitol's 'Malaya' Has Tracy and Stewart in Leads-- Two Imports Offered Walt Disney's Feature-Length 'Cinderella,' at the Mayfair, Heads List of Arrivals At the Capitol At the Criterion At the Rialto At the Palace At 55th St. Playhouse|website = The New York Times|first = Bosely|last = Crowther|date = February 23, 1950|accessdate = March 28, 2014|publisher = The New York Times Company}}</ref>\n\n[[Film4]] negatively described Cinderella as \"[[Flat character|one-dimensional]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.film4.com/reviews/1950/cinderella|title = Cinderella|publisher = Channel 4|website = Film4|accessdate = March 28, 2014}}</ref> Criticizing her design, [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]] ''wrote, \"If there is an obvious difference between ''Cinderella'' and such predecessors as ''[[Pinocchio (1940 film)|Pinocchio]]'' and ''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White]]'', it's in the general smoothing-out of the character's appearances,\" concluding, \"[[Snow White (Disney character)|Snow White]] herself looked fairly bland, but the other characters in the first decade of Disney animation had a lot of personality in their faces. They were allowed to look odd. ''Cinderella'' seems to come right out of its time, the bland postwar 1950s,\" likening the character's flawless design to that of a \"[[Draw Me a Map|Draw Me girl]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/cinderella-1987|title = Cinderella|publisher = Ebert Digital LLC|website = Roger Ebert|date = November 20, 1987|accessdate = March 28, 2014|first = Roger|last = Ebert}}</ref> Concerned about the negative effects Cinderella's passivity could possibly induce upon children, Nell Minow of [[Common Sense Media]] expressed, \"Cinderella is the quintessential passive heroine rescued by a male character ... so discussions about her meekness might be in order.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.commonsensemedia.org/movie-reviews/cinderella|title = Cinderella|website = Common Sense Media|accessdate = March 28, 2014|publisher = Common Sense Media Inc|date = October 31, 2005|last = Minow|first = Nell}}</ref> [[About.com]]'s Laurie Boeder simply described Cinderella as \"blah.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://classicfilm.about.com/od/childrensmovies/tp/Disney_Animated_Films_1950s.htm|title = Classic Disney Animated Movies of the 1950s|accessdate = April 15, 2014|website = About.com|publisher = About.com|last = Boeder|first = Laurie}}</ref> Desi Jedeikin of [[Smosh.com|Smosh]] included the character in the website's \"8 Fictional Characters That Are Horrible Role Models For Girls\" list, explaining, \"I'm like so happy that Cinderella found true love with a rich stranger who rescued her from her horrible life. But wouldn't it have been better if she did it for herself?\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.smosh.com/smosh-pit/articles/8-fictional-characters-are-horrible-role-models-girls|title = 8 Fictional Characters That Are Horrible Role Models For Girls|publisher = Defy Media, LLC|year = 2011|website = Smosh|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Jedeikin|first = Desi}}</ref> Additionally, critics have also expressed favoritism towards ''Cinderella''<nowiki/>'s [[Supporting Characters|supporting cast]] of [[Anthropomorphism|animal characters]], particularly the comic interaction and dynamic between her pet mice [[List of Disney's Cinderella characters#Jaq and Gus|Jaq and Gus]] and her stepfamily's pet cat [[Lucifer (Cinderella)|Lucifer]], often preferring them to Cinderella herself while noting ways in which the heroine is constantly being \"upstaged.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.filmthreat.com/reviews/8081/|title = Cinderella (1950) \u2013 In Her Shoes|website = Combustible Celluloid|publisher = Jeffrey M. Anderson|accessdate = March 28, 2014|last = Anderson|first = Jeffrey M.}}</ref>\n\nAmong, Cinderella's positive reviews, Michael Scheinfeld of ''[[TV Guide]] ''drew similarities between the character and [[Belle (Disney)|Belle]] from ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]] ''(1991), writing, ''[[Cinderella]]'' holds up better because the heroine seems timeless in her courage and resourcefulness, a closer cousin to Belle in Disney's ''Beauty and the Beast'' than to other fairytale protagonists.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://movies.tvguide.com/cinderella/review/110901|title = Cinderella|website = TV Guide|accessdate = March 28, 2014|publisher = CBS Interactive Inc|last = Scheinfeld|first = Michael}}</ref> Hailing Cinderella as \"the most famous and beloved princess of all time,\" [[HowStuffWorks]]' Vicki Arkoff defended the character, writing, \"highly sympathetic Cinderella is endlessly kind, patient, hard-working, and unassuming -- no matter how cruelly she is treated by her exaggerated, cartoonish foes.\" Arkoff elaborated, \"Unlike Disney's passive, naive Snow White, Disney's Cinderella is a princess who decides to take charge and change her life for the better, rather than just wait for things to happen that might solve her problem.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://lifestyle.howstuffworks.com/family/activities/movie-fun-night/how-disney-princess-works3.htm|title = Ultimate Guide to Disney Princess|publisher = HowStuffWorks, Inc|website = HowStuffWorks|accessdate = March 31, 2014|last = Arkoff|first = Vicki}}</ref> [[Review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]]' general consensus reads that, in addition to \"The rich colors, sweet songs, adorable mice,\" the \"endearing (if suffering) heroine make[s] ''Cinderella'' a nostalgically lovely charmer.\"<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nWoods herself has collected widespread acclaim for her performance. ''Variety ''wrote, \"Ilene Woods, as Cinderella\u2019s voice, uses a sweet [[soprano]].\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Craig Butler of [[AllMovie]] opined, \"[[Ilene Woods]] makes a marvelous Cinderella, her voice a combination of girlishness and sophistication; she also possesses a serenity and assurance which makes one feel she is more in control of her life than might be guessed by her surroundings.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.allmovie.com/movie/cinderella-v9656/review|title = Cinderella (1950)|accessdate = March 31, 2014|website = AllMovie|first = Craig|last = Butler|publisher = All Media Network, LLC}}</ref> At the time of Woods' death, animation critic and historian Charles Solomon told the ''Los Angeles Times'', \"one of the things about her performance is the warmth she gave the character. As soon as she began to speak, her voice meshed with Marc Davis' animation to create a heroine you liked instantly.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/03/local/la-me-ilene-woods-20100703|title = \nIlene Woods dies at 81; voice of Disney's Cinderella|accessdate = September 23, 2017|website = latimes.com|first = Dennis |last = McLellan|publisher = Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\n[[Lily James]]' portrayal as Cinderella in the [[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|live-action film adaptation]] was generally well-received by critics. [[Joe Morgenstern]] of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' commended James for her performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/cinderella-review-finds-new-soul-in-old-shoe-1426187867|title=\u2018Cinderella\u2019 Review: Finding New Soul in Old Shoe|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Morgenstern, Joe|date=March 12, 2015|accessdate=March 25, 2015}}</ref> ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Betsy Sharkey wrote that James makes the character \"seem as if the sweet and spirited young maiden is infused with an inner glow.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-cinderella-20150313-column.html?|title=In 'Cinderella,' no sly asides. Goodness and romance rule|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Sharkey, Betsy|date=March 12, 2015|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref> [[Richard Corliss]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' said that James created a version of the character that is \"both classic and modern.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3743894/cinderella-review-disney-live-action/|title=REVIEW: Disney\u2019s Live-Action Cinderella Rekindles Old Studio Magic|author=Corliss, Richard|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=March 13, 2015|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref>  Lawrence Toppman of ''[[The Charlotte Observer]]'' wrote that James played the character, \"with the right mixture of composure and pluck.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/ent-columns-blogs/lawrence-toppman/article13485305.html|title=Movie review: Sumptuous, subtle ''Cinderella'' satisfies in every way|work=The Charlotte Observer|author=Toppman, Lawrence|date=March 11, 2015|accessdate=February 10, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''{{'}}s David Rooney wrote that James brought \"unaffected sweetness\" to the role and also had \"lovely chemistry\" with her co-star [[Richard Madden]], who played the Prince.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/entry/view/id/914145|title = 'Cinderella': Berlin Review|author =Rooney, David|work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date = February 14, 2015|accessdate = February 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nCinderella has since become one of the most famous, recognizable and popular princesses, both fictional and non-fictional, of all-time.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://goarticles.com/article/10-Most-Famous-Fictional-Princesses-of-All-Time/2148070/|title = 10 Most Famous Fictional Princesses of All Time|publisher = GoArticles.com|accessdate = March 29, 2014|website = GoArticles.com|last = Bach|first = Kimberly|date = November 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://listphobia.com/2009/12/09/10-most-famous-fictional-princess-of-all-time/|title = 10 Most Famous Fictional Princess of all Time|publisher =|accessdate = March 29, 2014|website = Listphobia}}</ref> According to the ''[[San Antonio Express-News]]'', Cinderella is one of the ten most famous princesses of all-time.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.mysanantonio.com/list/article/10-most-famous-fictional-princesses-1402261.php|title = 10 most famous fictional princesses|date = May 30, 2011|accessdate = March 29, 2014|website = San Antonio Express-News|publisher = [[Hearst Newspapers, LLC]]}}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]] ''ranked the character the ninth greatest Disney Princess.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cosmopolitan.com/sex-love/advice/disney-princesses-ranked|title = The Definitive Ranking of Disney Princesses|publisher = Hearst Communications, Inc|website = Cosmopolitan|accessdate = March 29, 2014|last = Breslaw|first = Anna|date = December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 Woods received a [[Disney Legends]] award for her role as the voice of Cinderella. In 2010 she died at the age of 81, of [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.laweekly.com/informer/2010/07/07/ilene-woods-voice-of-disneys-cinderella-dies-at-81|title = Ilene Woods, Voice Of Disney's Cinderella, Dies At 81|website = LA Weekly|publisher = LA Weekly, LP|accessdate = March 29, 2014|date = July 7, 2010|last = Wei|first = Clarissa}}</ref> According to ''[[The Spokesman-Review]]'', Woods once said in an interview with ''[[Starlog]] ''that \"I love the idea that after I\u2019m gone, children will still be hearing my voice [as Cinderella].\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2010/jul/04/ilene-woods-voice-of-disneys-cinderella/|title = Ilene Woods, voice of Disney\u2019s Cinderella|website = The Spokesman-Review|publisher = The Spokesman-Review|accessdate = March 29, 2014|date = July 4, 2010}}</ref> In 2013, [[Film School Rejects]] recognized Woods as one of \"7 No-Name Actors Who Had Iconic Roles\", ranking the actress first and writing, \"Woods ... really set the bar high, as she managed to audition for the part of Cinderella without even realize she had done it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://filmschoolrejects.com/cinematic-listology/7-no-name-actors-who-had-iconic-roles.php|title = 7 No-Name Actors Who Had Iconic Roles|website = Film School Rejects|date = October 2, 2013|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = Reject Media, LLC|last = Bell|first = David Christopher}}</ref>\n\n[[Lily James]]' performance as Cinderella in the [[Cinderella (2015 Disney film)|2015 live-action film]] earned her nominations for the [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Sci-Fi/Fantasy]] and the award for \"Favorite Movie Actress\" at the [[2016 Kids' Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kids' Choice Awards: Adele, Justin Bieber, 'Star Wars' Among Nominees|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kids-choice-awards-adele-justin-861147|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/teen-choice-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201571268/ Teen Choice Awards 2015 Winners: Full List] ''Variety'', Retrieved April 17, 2017</ref> She also won the 2015 Breakthrough Award at the Harper's Bazaar Women of the Year Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcarpet-fashionawards.com/2015/11/04/lily-james-in-erdem-2015-harpers-bazaar-women-of-the-year-awards/|title=Lily James In Erdem \u2013 2015 Harper\u2019s Bazaar Women of the Year Awards|first=Catherine|last=Kallon|date=4 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208153455/http://www.redcarpet-fashionawards.com/2015/11/04/lily-james-in-erdem-2015-harpers-bazaar-women-of-the-year-awards/|archivedate=8 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Cultural impact===\nCulturally, Cinderella has had a profound influence on the [[fashion industry]]. According to Sarah Osman of [[Young Hollywood]], \"Cinderella\u2019s gown in this film is so iconic that it's become canon that Cinderella wears a light blue dress to the ball.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.younghollywood.com/scene/the-5-best-cinderella-film-adaptations.html|title = The 5 Best Cinderella Film Adaptations!|date = |accessdate = September 12, 2015|website = Young Hollywood|publisher = Young Hollywood LLC|last = Osman|first = Sarah}}</ref> To coincide with the release of the diamond edition of ''Cinderella ''in 2012, French footwear designer [[Christian Louboutin]] created and designed a contemporary rendition of the character's iconic glass slipper. In an interview with ''The Express Tribune'', Louboutin said that Cinderella is \"not only an iconic character when it comes to beauty, grace and fairytale love, but also shoes.\" The shoes are described as \"made of delicate lace [instead of glass] to give them a look of transparency, and adorned with butterfly designs at the vamp and atop the Swarovski-crystal covered heel,\" completed by Louboutin\u2019s signature red soles. Only twenty copies of the shoes were manufactured.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://tribune.com.pk/story/404613/christian-louboutins-cinderella-slipper-makes-fairytale-come-true/|title = Christian Louboutin\u2019s Cinderella slipper makes fairytale come true|website = The Express Tribune|publisher = The Express Tribune News Network|date = July 7, 2012|accessdate = March 29, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]] ''ranked Cinderella tenth in its article \"Disney Princesses: Ranking Their Hairdos -- and Don'ts!\", writing, \"The lowly maid's typically rage-inducing bangs somehow develop an almost stately character once the rest of her follicular baggage has been swept into an updo closely resembling a perky butt.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20609151_20445104_20880962,00.html#20880960|title = Disney Princesses: Ranking Their Hairdos -- and Don'ts!|date = March 27, 2014|website = Entertainment Weekly|publisher = Entertainment Weekly Inc|accessdate = March 29, 2014|last = Barrett|first = Annie}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[86th Academy Awards]] in 2014, Kenyan actress and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] recipient [[Lupita Nyong'o]] donned \"a light blue [[Prada]] gown.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.popsugar.com/Lupita-Nyongo-Looks-Like-Cinderella-Oscars-2014-34230698|title = Lupita Nyong'o Looks Just Like Cinderella at the Oscars|date = March 2, 2014|website = PopSugar|publisher = POPSUGAR Inc|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Whitney|first = Alyse}}</ref> Subsequently, the media responded by drawing similarities between Nyong'o's dress and Cinderella's [[ballgown]]. ''Cosmopolitan ''wrote that Nyong'o \"took a cue from Disney with a blue iridescent gown and matching headband ''[[a la]]'' Cinderella,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cosmopolitan.com/celebrity/news/lupita-nyongo-oscars|title = Lupita Nyong'o Is In A Cinderella Gown At The Oscars|publisher = Hearst Communications, Inc|website = Cosmopolitan|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Breslaw|first = Anna|date = March 2, 2014}}</ref> while the ''[[New York Daily News|Daily News]] ''similarly opined \"channeled another Disney princess for her Oscars gown.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/oscars/lupita-nyong-channels-cinderella-oscars-gown-article-1.1708787|title = Oscars 2014: Lupita Nyong\u2019o\u2019s powder blue princess gown draws comparison to Cinderella|publisher = NYDailyNews.com|website = Daily News|accessdate = March 30, 2014|date = March 3, 2014|last = Monde|first = Chiderah}}</ref> Acknowledging the comparisons, Nyong'o's stylist Micaela Erlanger described the actress' appearance as \"Lupita + Cinderella = Lupitarella.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscars-fashion-2014-lupita-nyongo-685120|title = Oscars Fashion: Lupita Nyong'o Sparkles in a Fred Leighton Headband|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = The Hollywood Reporter|website = The Hollywood Reporter|last = Chan|first = Stephanie|date = March 2, 2014}}</ref> Additionally, several critics have deemed Nyong'o's success a \"Cinderella story.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.hitfix.com/in-contention/12-years-a-slave-star-lupita-nyongo-holds-off-jennifer-lawrence-to-win-the-best-supporting-actress-oscar|title = '12 Years a Slave' star Lupita Nyong'o holds off Jennifer Lawrence to win the Best Supporting Actress Oscar|publisher = HitFix, Inc|date = March 2, 2014|accessdate = March 30, 2014|website = HitFix|last = Tapley|first = Kristopher}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cnn.com/2014/03/03/opinion/davis-lupita-nyongo/|title = Lupita, a Cinderella for everybody|website = CNN|accessdate = March 30, 2014|publisher = Cable News Network|last = Davis|first = Michaela Angela|date = March 3, 2014}}</ref> According to [[MTV]], several other Academy Award attendants wore similar outfits that were reminiscent of Disney characters in addition to Nyong'o.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1723322/oscars-2014-red-carpet-disney-princesses.jhtml|title = Why Is Everyone At The Oscars Dressed Like Disney Characters?|website = MTV|publisher = Viacom International Inc|date = Mar 2, 2014|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Zalben|first = Alex}}</ref>\n\n====Makeover sequence====\nThe iconic \"[[Bibbidi-Bobbidi-Boo]]\" [[Number (music)|musical sequence]] in which Cinderella's Fairy Godmother magically transforms the character's tattered rags into a beautiful ball gown has garnered widespread critical acclaim, receiving positive reviews, accolades and recognition from several entertainment critics. AllMovie described the sequence as \"splendidly done,\"<ref name=\":3\" /> while HitFix deemed it the film's best moment.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.hitfix.com/galleries/overlay/top-20-disney-animated-films-of-all-time|title = Top 20 Disney Animated Films of All-Time|website = HitFix|publisher = HitFix, Inc|date = November 25, 2013|accessdate = April 16, 2014|last = Lasser|first = Josh}}</ref> According to [[Disney.com]], the transformation of Cinderella's dress into a ballgown remains a common favorite and \"one of the most iconic pieces of Disney animation because of what it means for the titular character.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogs.disney.com/disney-style/fashion/2014/05/14/the-best-disney-style-moments-of-transformation/|title = The Best Disney Style Moments of Transformation|date = May 15, 2014|accessdate = May 17, 2014|website = Official Disney Blogs|publisher = Disney|last =|first =}}</ref> StyleCaster wrote that the scene is responsible for introducing the common \"movie makeover,\" writing, \"Ever since Cinderella ditched those rags and threw on a ball gown and a pair of glass slippers, movie audiences have fallen for the beloved transformation storyline.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.stylecaster.com/10-amazing-movie-makeovers-devil-wears-prada-girls/|title = 10 Amazing Movie Makeovers, From \"The Devil Wears Prada\" to \"Mean Girls\"|website = StyleCaster|publisher = StyleCaster INC|accessdate = March 28, 2014|date = November 27, 2012|last = Cain|first = Spencer}}</ref> Featuring Cinderella in its list of \"13 movie makeovers that still totally rock our socks off\", ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] ''summarized the scene's role in the film as \"The movie makeover that sees a merry band of rodents help Cindera[''sic'']lla to make the perfect dress, eventually go to the ball and ultimately win the heart of a prince.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/news/features/2013/10/brilliant-movie-makeovers-sandy-grease-cinderella-pretty-woman|title = 13 movie makeovers that still totally rock our socks off|website = Glamour|publisher = Nast UK|date = October 11, 2013|last = Powell|first = Hannah Lyons|accessdate = March 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Oprah.com]] also included Cinderella in its \"Favorite Movie Makeovers\" list, accrediting the film and Disney with \"first introducing us to the head-to-toe makeover,\" concluding, \" Unrealistic expectations are born.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.oprah.com/entertainment/Screening-Room-Favorite-Movie-Makeovers|title = Favorite Movie Makeovers|date = April 27, 2009|website = Oprah.com|publisher = Harpo Productions, Inc|accessdate = March 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLikewise, both the sequence and Cinderella's magical transformation have been featured on several \"best movie makeover\" [[countdown]] lists. On ''[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]]''<nowiki/>'s list of the \"50 Best Movie Makeovers\", Cinderella placed first, with the magazine labeling her the \"Recipient of the original makeover.\" Additionally, ''Stylist'' coined the list's other candidates \"Cinematic Cinderellas,\" alluding to the character's legacy.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.stylist.co.uk/beauty/50-best-movie-makeovers#item-50|title = 50 Best Movie Makeovers|date = April 24, 2013|website = Stylist|publisher = Stylist|accessdate = March 29, 2014}}</ref> ''[[InStyle]]'' ranked ''Cinderella ''second on its list of \"The Best Movie Makeovers\", writing, \"Cinderella\u2019s fairy tale transformation is the stuff that many a little girl's real-life makeover dreams are made of.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.instyle.com/instyle/package/general/photos/0,,20542054_20572501_21088407,00.html|title = The Best Movie Makeovers \u2013 Cinderella (1950)|accessdate = March 29, 2014|website = InStyle}}</ref> Hailing it as \"[The] makeover of makeovers\" and \"the movie that started it all,\" ''[[The Independent Florida Alligator]]'' ranked ''Cinderella ''first in its list of \"The best of movie makeovers\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.alligator.org/blogs/thursday/article_694a3c88-d483-11e2-acb1-001a4bcf887a.html|title = The best of movie makeovers|website = The Independent Florida Alligator|publisher = The Independent Florida Alligator|date = June 13, 2013|last = Champalanne|first = Michelle|accessdate = March 29, 2014}}</ref> Style Blazer also ranked ''Cinderella'' second on its list of the \"Top 11 Favorite Makeover Movies of All Time\", concluding, \"Cinderella and her pauper to princess makeover have already gone down in movie history as one of the best transformations.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://styleblazer.com/58275/top-11-favorite-makeover-movies-of-all-time-see-which-ones-made-our-list/10/|title = Top 11 Favorite Makeover Movies of All Time (See Which Ones Made Our List!)|website = Style Blazer|publisher = Moguldom Media Group|date = June 18, 2012|accessdate = March 28, 2014|last = Lawrence|first = Tameika}}</ref> Calling Cinderella the \"Original Fairy Godmother ... makeover,\" ''[[Total Beauty Media|Total Beauty]] ''ranked the character fifth in its article \"11 Best Movie Makeovers\".<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.totalbeauty.com/content/slideshows/11-best-movie-makeovers/page5|title = 11 Best Movie Makeovers|website = Total Beauty|date = July 22, 2013|publisher = Total Beauty Media, Inc|accessdate = March 30, 2014|last = Glick|first = Lila}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Disney}}\n{{commons category|Cinderella (Disney character)}}\n*[http://princess.disney.com/cinderella Cinderella] at [http://princess.disney.com/ Disney Princess]\n\n{{Disney's Cinderella}}\n{{Disney Princess}}\n{{Cinderella (Fairy tale)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cinderella (Disney Character)}}\n[[Category:Cinderella (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Cinderella characters]]\n[[Category:Disney Princess characters]]\n[[Category:Kingdom Hearts characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional maids]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 1950]]\n", "name_user": "98.210.204.197", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cinderella_(Disney_character)"}
